  "name": "Morrison COU2 — VAD hemolysis credibility assessment",
  "couName": "VAD use",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under ventricular assist device (VAD) conditions. COU2 evaluates whether the computational model can predict absolute hemolysis levels for a Class III VAD device at Model Risk Level 5. Higher model risk drives stricter credibility requirements; Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification is performed but all credibility factor gaps remain. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all with achieved levels below required levels), 6 factors not assessed (flagged as epistemic gaps at MRL 5). Decision: Not accepted.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Low",
  "deviceClass": "Class III",
  "modelRiskLevel": 5,
  "decision": "Not accepted",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/morrison/req/vad-hemolysis-mrl5",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/morrison/claim/cfd-hemolysis-absolute-vad",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/morrison/model/cfd-centrifugal-pump-hemolysis",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental",
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/montecarlo-uq-samples-vad"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/pump-hemolysis-bench-vad",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Bench-scale hemolysis validation against FDA pump experimental data",
      "description": "CFD predictions of normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against published FDA generic pump experimental measurements at 5 operating points. Mean absolute error 38%; model systematically under-predicts at high shear-stress conditions. Monte Carlo UQ campaign (n=2000 Latin hypercube samples) was executed to propagate rheological and geometric uncertainty through the hemolysis power-law model; sensitivity indices were computed internally within the UQ campaign but are not formally linked as a structured sensitivity analysis record. Validation activity confirms substantial model form error at MRL 5 conditions."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/mesh-convergence-vad",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh convergence study for centrifugal pump impeller region",
      "description": "Three-level mesh refinement study (coarse 2.1M, medium 5.8M, fine 14.2M cells) using Richardson extrapolation. Grid convergence index (GCI) for NIH quantity of interest: 12.4% on medium mesh, 4.1% on fine mesh. Fine mesh adopted for all production runs. Discretization error remains non-negligible relative to MRL 5 required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/code-verification-vad",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Manufactured solution code verification for hemolysis transport scalar",
      "description": "Method of manufactured solutions applied to the passive scalar hemolysis transport equation in a simplified channel geometry. L2 norm of error converges at 1.87 order (expected 2nd order). Minor superconvergence failure attributed to boundary condition implementation; documented as known deviation. Numerical solver residuals reach 1e-6 for all momentum and scalar equations."
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4037497",
  "wasAttributedTo": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-division-of-applied-mechanics",
